<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>Artemon son of Adrastos the son of Dionysios the son of Dinomachos dedicated the six columns at his own expense to the People, with their capitals</p>
</div>
<div type="commentary">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p>These four columns are from a group of six dedicated by Artemon. Another two survive from the 14 dedicated by Nestor and Zenon, <xref type="inscription" n="1111" href="050205">5.205</xref>, (=Mendel 173). For further column dedications from the Hadrianic Baths see <xref type="iAph">1113</xref> (=Boulanger B Page 23 no. 29), and <xref type="inscription" n="1112" href="050003">5.3</xref> (=84.64).</p>
</div>
<div type="history" n="locations">
<head>Locations</head>
<p>
 <rs type="origLocation">, on the north side of the 'Salle au vingt colonnes', at the south east corner of the east court of the <rs type="monuList">Hadrianic baths</rs>.</rs> <rs type="found">i : <rs type="monuList">South Agora</rs>, north portico; ii and iii: <rs type="monuList">Hadrianic Baths</rs>, 'Salle au vingt colonnes'; iv <rs type="monuList">Tetrastoon</rs>, reused in the south colonnade.</rs>
; Last known location: <rs type="lastLocation">i and iii,  Museum; ii and iv, Findspot.</rs>
</p>
</div>
<div type="history" n="record">
<head>History of Recording</head>
<p>The text informs us that there were originally 6 columns, presumably each bearing the same text; Mendel copied ii and cited i (notebook A 7, a; C, 9); all four recorded by the NYU expedition: i in 1985, ii and iii in 1988 (<rs type="invNo">88.18</rs>), iv in 1978 (<rs type="siteNo">Theatre 20</rs>).</p>
</div>
